<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY PERSPECTIVE; 
</P>
<P>
IN SEARCH OF THE STEALTH SENATOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Where was Wadie? That's the question 40th District voters should be asking 
themselves about state Sen. Deddeh's attendance record during the past 
legislative session -- and the final, crucial week in particular. 
</P>
<P>
A computer analysis shows that Deddeh (D-Bonita) missed 43% of the Senate's 
votes, an absentee rate surpassed only by a Los Angeles senator hospitalized 
for alcoholism and a heart problem. 
</P>
<P>
Particularly disturbing, however, was Deddeh's decision to miss the last, 
hectic week of the session, when landmark oil-spill legislation was passed, 
$3.6 billion in bonds were put on the November ballot and a bill requiring 
earthquake insurance for state homeowners was finalized. Deddeh spent the week 
at home, entertaining relatives in the days before his only son's wedding. 
</P>
<P>
Then he compounded that misjudgment with this remark to a Times reporter: "The 
bills that were before us -- nothing was crucial, nothing was important," 
Deddeh said. "As far as I was concerned, if those bills were not passed at all, 
the state would probably be better off for it." 
</P>
<P>
Deddeh is dead wrong in that assessment. His statement that he was ready to fly 
to Sacramento on a moment's notice, if needed to break a deadlock, is proof. 
Moreover, South Bay and San Diego voters didn't elect the 24-year incumbent to 
stay home as the Legislature cast more than 800 end-of-session votes. He should 
have been in Sacramento attending to statewide and local issues. 
</P>
<P>
The computer tally of Deddeh's votes somewhat exaggerates his absences. For 
example, it makes no allowances for conflicting committee meetings that force 
legislators to miss some votes. But Deddeh's 43% absence rate is almost three 
times the Senate average. 
</P>
<P>
Most of his colleagues in the San Diego delegation achieved considerably better 
attendance records. 
</P>
<P>
As Deddeh goes through a reelection campaign this fall, he should explain his 
actions to constituents casting their votes this November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
