<HEADLINE>
<P>
4 KILLED IN CRASH OF PRIVATE JET IN SAN LUIS OBISPO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN LUIS OBISPO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A private jet crashed as the pilot attempted to land in a heavy fog Monday 
morning at a municipal airport, killing all four people aboard, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The names of the occupants were not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
The twin-engine Cessna Citation, registered to a helicopter company in Newport, 
Ore., had taken off from Van Nuys Airport. It crashed at 7:03 a.m. in a field 
about three miles northwest of the San Luis Obispo Airport, Federal Aviation 
Administration spokesman Fred O'Donnell said. 
</P>
<P>
The cause of the crash was not immediately known. 
</P>
<P>
Minutes before the crash, the pilot reported that the craft had passed the 
airport's outer marker and was headed for a landing. 
</P>
<P>
San Luis Obispo County Sheriff's Sgt. Leon Cole said four people were confirmed 
dead. 
</P>
<P>
Searchers spent several hours looking for a fifth person originally reported to 
be aboard. It was later determined that the person did not board the plane, 
Cole said. 
</P>
<P>
Wreckage from the Citation, a jet that can carry as many as a dozen people, was 
strewn over a wide area east of Madonna Road. Firefighters put out several spot 
fires that erupted in some parts of the wreckage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Firefighters work to extinguish flames after the crash Monday of a 
Cessna Citation in San Luis Obispo. All four people aboard the plane were 
killed. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
