<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONGRESS MOVES TO DELAY BUDGET CUTS; WHITE HOUSE VOWS FIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Congress today took the first step to delay $85 billion in imminent spending 
cuts, while the White House said it would rather "negotiate into the night" 
than accept a delay. 
</P>
<P>
Republicans were almost unanimous in opposition as the House Appropriations 
Committee approved, 32 to 20, a catchall bill that would keep government 
operations going for an additional 20 days -- until Oct. 20 -- to provide more 
time for negotiators to reach an agreement on deficit reduction. 
</P>
<P>
In an effort to discourage President Bush's promised veto, the committee 
attached to the bill an additional $2.1 billion to finance U.S. participation 
in Operation Desert Shield in the Persian Gulf. 
</P>
<P>
The committee sidestepped another foreign policy question, Bush's proposal to 
forgive $6.7 billion of Egypt's debt in appreciation of Cairo's assistance in 
the gulf. 
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater repeated today that Bush would veto any 
legislation that would delay across-the-board spending reductions. 
</P>
<P>
The cuts -- called a sequester -- will take place unless the targets of the 
Gramm-Rudman law are modified or delayed and will mean reductions of up to 40% 
throughout the government. 
</P>
<P>
"We want to avoid a sequester. We are willing to negotiate into the night," 
Fitzwater said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
