<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: BAKING SODA, CORN STARCH TEAM TO CONQUER UNDERARM ODOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON and TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I'm having difficulty finding an underarm deodorant that will not 
cause irritation. Within a day of using any deodorant, my skin develops a deep 
red irritation. I have even tried natural products from health food stores, but 
with no success. 
</P>
<P>
The only non-irritant I have found is baby powder and corn starch, but I have a 
stressful job and require more protection. Help! 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Here are some hints to help prevent irritation from antiperspirants and 
underarm deodorants. Never apply them after showering or shaving under your 
arms. For greatest effectiveness, antiperspirants should be applied to dry skin 
in the evening before bed. 
</P>
<P>
If that doesn't work, here is a recommendation you may find helpful. A reader 
of this column offers the following: 
</P>
<P>
"After reading about underarm odor, I feel led to write you about a simple 
solution to this problem. My daughter has underarm odor. I used to nag her to 
wash herself better and use deodorant, but it never helped. One day I read 
about baking soda. After much arguing, my daughter agreed to give it a try. 
That was the end of her objectionable smell. But if she doesn't use it, I can 
still smell her from across the room. Baking soda really works, and it is very 
inexpensive." 
</P>
<P>
This isn't the first time we have heard of this home remedy. A baking soda and 
corn starch combination, dusted on, can be effective for some people. 
</P>
<P>
Q. When I read the letter from the woman whose husband caught genital herpes 
from her after 10 years of marriage, I wept. The pain she expressed reminded me 
of the anguish my husband and I went through ourselves. 
</P>
<P>
Herpes is a cruel disease, but Zovirax has helped us cope with the physical 
symptoms. Our local support group has given us strength to deal with the 
emotional symptoms. I highly recommend the Herpes Resource Center, which can 
put people in touch with a support group in their area. The number is (919) 
361-2120. 
</P>
<P>
A. Thanks for the tip. People with herpes need all the help they can get. There 
is also a newsletter put out by the Herpes Resource Center with information on 
research and practical advice on dealing with this viral infection. Another 
source of information about herpes and other sexually transmitted diseases is 
the STD hotline: (800) 227-8922. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
